snippet.textDisplay: I wouldn't put the blame on both directors because well, not only that they both had a vision, but they were both doing their damn jobs! By anything I'm putting the blame towards Disney for not having a roadmap for this trilogy. Disney was literally saying "F**k it" and just slapped together a trilogy that sadly went nowhere, and look at where we are now. Yes, Rian Johnson did mess up the trilogy with "The Last Jedi" after J.J. Abrams passed the torch to him and he tosses it off the cliff, I get it, but he was only doing his job. Rian was making his own vision of the story, and we already know how that turned out. Even out of all that brouhaha, Disney still decided to not tell him what should have been planned out the get-go. Like hell, take a look at the MCU for example, even though they have different directors with different visions, both Marvel and Kevin Feige had a roadmap going forward. If Disney actually cared, they could have make an actual roadmap to make a perfect storyline experience (like how the MCU did with the Infinity Saga), but instead they gave us a broken roadmap that's more reminiscent to Bioware's Anthem, a non-existence plot, characters that you don't give a sh*t about, Unnecessary shipping (which honestly makes me cringe), Nostalgia for the sake of... well nostalgia (not always a bad thing if done right), and character decisions that left everyone in an anger state (Game of Thrones, Season 8). And that's pretty much I could get behind from all of this mess of a film. Now to be perfectly honest, I would rather watch the Prequels again because, even though they had their faults, at least you could actually tell that George Lucas has a vision on the franchise, unlike what Disney in-visioned, or lack-there-of.

snippet.textDisplay:
I felt like the ending was similar to ending of the last Harry Potter movie... for 3 reasons...

1) When Palpatine sucked out Rey and Kylo's life, it was similar to the "Dementors Kiss" which lets the Dementors suck out a person's soul in the Harry Potter movies.

2) Also, i'm guessing that Sith people don’t turn into Sith ghosts, but they can put their force essence into objects. So this to me was kind of like Rey being a possible "horacrux" (like Harry Potter was), and just like how a part of Voldemort was stuck inside of Harry Potter (and other horacrux created objects) so that Voldemort could live on forever, Palpatine tried to put his essence inside of "Rey the horacrux" so that he and the sith order could live on forever too.

3) And finally, when Rey deflected the force lightning back at Palpatine and destroyed him, it was the same as when Harry Potter deflected Voldermort's attack back at him and destroyed Voldemort.

Still though.... with what they had to work with... and they ain't George Lucas... we still enjoyed the movie.

snippet.textDisplay: In my opinion, I thought the new movie was actually really good. I went in expecting to see a movie that was going to end up bad, but it actually had lots and lots of cool surprises. With stats alone, this movie made over 200 million with just 2 opening days at the theaters. All thr characters played really well, and there wasnt a part I got bored at. The problem for people is if you go to watch a movie that you kept telling yourself is going to be bad, then you'll still think its bad. You'll only look at the bad things and that will keep you from seeing most of the movie in a good way. And if you said all the spoilers are true, then why the hell did you watch the spoilers? You going to see the movie anyways. I went there without seeing any spoiler. Not a single one. I just hate how people hate on a movie that did so well. It literally came out on top of the other movies released on the same days. Plus, some theaters like mine actually did a little battle before the movie started, and two staff members dueled with sabers. Idk what else to say but this movie was badass, and way better than the previous 2.
